				<p>
					To adjust their calendar they used <em>the Sothic cycle</em> as a long-term framework to keep it aligned with the seasons. This cycle was based
					on the rising of the star Sirius (Greek: <gr>Σωθις</gr>, <i>Sothis</i>) and would have emerged later rather than earlier as the Egyptians
					tracked the calendar’s drift against Sirius’s rising. Every 1460 years, Sirius would appear to rise above the eastern horizon on the same
					day according to their calendar, marking a cyclical ‘reset’ of their calendar year with the astronomical phenomena. For most of Egypt's
					history, a year began on <i>I Akhet, day 1</i>. In Ptolemaic times, the first day was <i>1 Thoth</i>.
				</p>

